# Quick look at BTC 1-hour data

I want to check the price behavior and volume trends over the last 100 candles before feeding anything into a model. Just a basic visual check to see if there are any obvious patterns or outliers.
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

df = pd.read_csv('../data/btc_sample.csv')
df.head()

## Returns distribution

Let's see how the hourly returns are spread out. If the distribution is too skewed, it might mess up the model later. Good to know before engineering features.
df['returns'] = df['close'].pct_change()
df['returns'].hist(bins=30)
plt.title('Hourly Returns Distribution')
plt.show()

## Observations

The distribution has a bit of positive skew and some fat tails. This means extreme moves happen more often than a normal distribution would predict. Tree-based models (like RandomForest) handle this pretty well, so I won't normalize the data for the demo.
# RandomForest quick test on BTC

Just a raw test to see if a basic classifier can pick up any signal from the price action. I'm not tuning hyperparameters here, just checking if the data has any predictive value at all.

from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score

df = pd.read_csv('../data/btc_sample.csv')
df['returns'] = df['close'].pct_change()
df['vol_ma'] = df['volume'].rolling(5).mean()
df['target'] = (df['returns'].shift(-1) > 0).astype(int)
df = df.dropna()

X = df[['returns', 'vol_ma']]
y = df['target']

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)

model = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=10)
model.fit(X_train, y_train)

preds = model.predict(X_test)
acc = accuracy_score(y_test, preds)
print(f"Test Accuracy: {acc:.2f}")

## Test results

Accuracy is around 0.55. That's barely better than a coin flip (0.5). 

This confirms that using only 2 basic features (returns and volume MA) isn't enough. The model needs more engineered features like RSI, MACD, or longer-term moving averages to capture real patterns. 

I'll leave this simple model here as a baseline, but for the actual TR-AMB production bots, we'll be using a much richer feature set.



